    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "interesting. u say \"most analysts\" see it as a failure though. isn't it true that a lot of people argue the real failure was actually the lack of support for the regime change, and that if the US had stayed committed to building a democratic state instead of just pulling out, it could've been a huge win for stability in the region? like, was the failure the intervention itself or just the lack of follow-through?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That argument highlights a critical distinction: the failure might lie more in the execution of the post-intervention phase than the initial military action. Many critics argue that the US prioritized regime change over nation-building, a common pitfall in modern military intervention. Without a dedicated, long-term stabilization and democratic-building commitment, even a successful military operation can quickly devolve into chaos. Thus, the primary strategic failure was arguably the insufficient commitment to the required political and governance aftermath.",
      "source": "target",
